# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baduy-people
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] The **Abui people**, also known as **Barawahing**, **Barue**, or **Namatalaki**, are an indigenous ethnic group residing on Alor Island, East Nusa Tenggara, Indonesia.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Abui people are spread across the districts of South Alor, East Alor, and Northwest Alor in Alor Regency.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Abui people speak the Abui language, which is a Papuan (non-Austronesian) language, as well as Indonesian, and a Malay-based creole known as Alor Malay.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] The term *Abui* is an Abui word that means ‘mountains’ or alternatively ‘enclosed place’.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Abui people refer to themselves as *Abui loku*, literally meaning 'the mountain people'.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] The bare term *Abui* is often associated with the large mountain range in central Alor, *Abui foka*, and is often contrasted to the smaller mountain range in the Kabola/Adang speaking area *Abui kiding* in the Bird's Head of Alor.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] The language is referred to as *Abui tanga* in the Takalelang variety (the most well-studied variety) and *Abui laral* in the Welai, Mola, and Mainang varieties.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] The glossonym *Abui* was first introduced by Cora Du Bois in the late 1930s after the ethnonym was already in circulation.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] This ethnonym is also used in Alor Malay/Indonesian to refer to Abui speakers.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] According to Abui oral tradition, Abui people settled in Alor in ancient times and did not find other settlers there.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Later some of them moved to the Kabola peninsula.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] The same tradition accounts that they dwelled in caves in the mountains in the Mainang area.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] In this area also some rock art is found.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Abui refer to neighbouring tribes as ‘younger siblings’ or as ‘new arrivals’.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] However, the oral tradition in Alor serves too often as a political instrument.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] The oral tradition has not been verified by archaeological research yet.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] The American anthropologist Cora Du Bois studied and lived among Abui people from 1937 to 1939 in the village of Atimelang, resulting in the publication, *The People of Alor.* Around the same time, the Dutch sociologist Martha Margaretha Nicolspeyer published a study of the Abui social structure.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Abui people from Takpala village engage in a traditional dance known as *lego-lego*, in which dancers move in a circular pattern.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Other Abui dance is the Cakalele used for welcoming guests.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] The original religion of the inhabitants of Alor Islands was animistic until much later when Protestant missionaries arrived.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Majority of the Alor Island communities are Christians, except for those living along the coast line tend to be Muslims as most of the Muslims living there migrated from other islands.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] The Abui people generally are predominantly Protestant.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] However, their beliefs have animistic influences as well.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Catholic communities are found in Kalabahi and particularly among the Abui people in Takalelang and Mainang.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] There is also one Muslim Abui community, found in the coastal village of Nurdin.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Abui speakers are mainly farmers, just like other inhabitants of Alor.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] However, in mountainous areas hunting and gathering is also an important supplement to the staple diet of corn, cassava, and rice.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] In the coastal areas, which are less favourable for agriculture, many farmers have switched to fishing, the traditional activity of the Austronesian population.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Traditional livestock are pigs and chicken.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] However, livestock seldom supplement the diet due to frequent swine fever and poultry diseases.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Thus, the diet is not well balanced, often resulting in poor health conditions and anaemia, especially among children and women.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] In the mountainous areas the situation is better as traditional hunting provides a more balanced diet.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] The mountains also favour a number of important cash crops such as tamarind, coconuts, coffee, cloves, cocoa, cashew nuts, candlenuts (Aleurites moluccana), vanilla, almonds (Canarium) and tobacco.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] These provide the farmers with additional income, which results in generally better living standards than for people in the coastal areas.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] The Abui "traditional village of Takpala" (*kampung tradisional Takpala*) is a tourist destination consisting of a small cluster of traditional houses on a hillside.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Visitors watch performances, pose for photographs in traditional attire, and buy handicrafts.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] In 1980, the Takpala Village won second place for most traditional village at the national level.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] There are also many Western researchers who would visit the village in order to study the culture, lifestyle and language of the Abui people.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Ever since then, Takpala Village is considered a cultural heritage area by the Alor Regency and a tourist destination.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Aside from cultural tourism, Alor Island is also known as a world class diving location.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] To date, there are 42 registered diving sites in Alor Island.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] Educational facilities in the Abui area are limited to elementary and secondary schools in district capitals.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] The nearest university is in Kalabahi, which offers limited training in economy, law, English and computer science.
[src:baduy-people/abui-people] The more significant educational institutions are found in Kupang, the provincial capital of East Nusa Tenggara.
[src:baduy-people/abun-people] The **Abun**, previously also known as **Wen**, **Karon Pantai**, or **Coastal Karon**, are an ethnic group of New Guinea, residing in the Sausapor district of the Tambrauw Regency in the province of Southwest Papua.
[src:baduy-people/abun-people] They live in the Sausapor, Jokte, Emaos and Uigwem villages of Sausapor and are of the clans Yekwam, Yenjau, Yeblo, Yesnath, Yenbra, Yenggrem, Yesomkor, Yerin, Yeror, Yewen, Yemam and Yesian.
[src:baduy-people/abun-people] The Abun were originally the *Wen* from the Tambrauw Mountains (locally called the **Ndokdar** Mountains).
[src:baduy-people/abun-people] After having socialized with the Biak people near the coastline, they were then called the *Karon* (meaning: *the people from within*), while the ones who continued to stay in the mountains were called *Karondori*.
[src:baduy-people/abun-people] However, this eventually had negative connotations and they adopted the name *Abun* (meaning: *tribal language*), which originally was used for the name of their language.
[src:baduy-people/abun-people] 21 categorizations of bananas are named and are divided by whether it is eaten fresh or cooked first.
[src:baduy-people/abun-people] The harvesting of the bananas are done by both men and women; typically but not necessarily being the men chopping the trees and the women transporting the fruit.
[src:baduy-people/abun-people] On most days, they head to the farms which are around 1–2 km away between 8–9 am (WIT) and return home by 5pm.
[src:baduy-people/abun-people] The highest ranking leader of the Abun tradition is called the **Yekwesu** who governs the **Wis** in the village.
[src:baduy-people/abun-people] Every **Wis** also has a leader **Yehos** who help the **Yekwesu** govern.
[src:baduy-people/abun-people] Anyone can become a **Yekwesu** with their own efforts, but has to be rich in cloth (*kain timor*), and also be brave, wise, generous and diplomatic.
[src:baduy-people/abun-people] The Salara is a traditional dance performed in a group with a snake-like formation possibly in a circle; holding one another by the arms to form a chain.
[src:baduy-people/abun-people] It is said that the ancestors of the Abun people turned into a snake and left the mountains for the beach.
[src:baduy-people/abun-people] The dance is similar to the other *Tari Tumbu Tanah* of the Arfak people.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The **Acehnese** (Acehnese: *Ureueng Acèh* [uˈrɯ(ə̯)ŋ aˈcɛh], Husaini: *Ureuëng Atjèh*, Jawoe: اورڠ اچيه‎; Indonesian: *Orang Aceh*), also written as **Achinese**, are an Austronesian ethnic group native to Aceh, a province on the northernmost tip of the island of Sumatra in Indonesia.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The area has a history of political struggle against the Dutch colonial rule.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The vast majority of Acehnese people are Muslims.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The Acehnese people are also referred to by other names such as **Lam Muri**, **Lambri**, **Akhir**, **Achin**, **Asji**, **A-tse** and **Atse**.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Their language, Acehnese, belongs to the Aceh–Chamic group of Malayo-Polynesian of the Austronesian language family.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The Acehnese were, for a time, partially Hinduised, as evident from their traditions and the many Sanskrit words in their language.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Trade with the Islamic world resulted in the Islamization of the population and gradually displaced older religions practiced by the Acehnese.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] As a result, the Acehnese have been Muslims for many centuries.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The estimated number of Acehnese ranges between 3,526,000 people to 4.2 million people.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Traditionally, Acehnese are agriculturists, metal-workers and weavers.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Traditionally matrilocal, their social organisation is communal.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] They live in *gampôngs*, which combine to form districts known as *mukims*.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The golden era of Acehnese culture began in the 16th century, along with the rise of the Islamic Aceh Sultanate and later reaching its peak in the 17th century.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Generally, the Acehnese people are regarded as conservative adherents to the Islamic faith and also as militant fighters against the colonial conquest of the Portuguese Empire and the Dutch Empire.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Aceh came to international attention as being the hardest-hit region of the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake with 120,000 people dead.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Archaeological evidence show that the earliest inhabitants of Aceh were from the Pleistocene age, where they lived in the west coast of Aceh (Langsa and Aceh Tamiang Regency region) and exhibited Australomelanesoid characteristics.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] They mainly relied on a diet of seafood, including various types of shellfish, as well as land animals.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The inhabitants are known to have used fire and practiced rituals of burial.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The migration of the modern-day indigenous tribes, such as the Mantr people and the Lhan people (Proto-Malay), as well as the Chams, Malays and Minangkabau people (Deutero-Malay) who arrived later, formed the *pribumi* dwellers of Aceh.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Foreign ethnic groups, especially Indians, as well as a small amount of Arabs, Persians, Turks, and Portuguese also compromise the ancestry of the Acehnese people.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The strategic position of Aceh in the northern tip of the Sumatra island for thousands of years has allowed the region to become a haven for trade and inter-marriage of various people groups, namely those involved in the sea trade route from the Middle East to China.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The geographic gap between other Chamic languages and Acehnese may have led to influence on Indochinese speakers of Chamic languages from Malay, Khmer, Thai, and Vietnamese over the following two thousand years.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Chinese and Indian sources from 500 CE and onward mention that there was a settlement in northernmost Sumatra (Aceh) which was called P'o-lu.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Many scholars believe that P'o-lu was close to the what is now Banda Aceh.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] These sources also state that the average person wore cotton clothing while the ruling elite wore silk.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The Chinese annals also claim that the local people were Buddhist.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Acehnese folklore states that the earliest people of Aceh came from indigenous tribes such as the Mante people and the Lhan people.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The Mante people were a local native group believed to be related to the Batak, Gayonese and Alas people, while the Lhan people are allegedly still related to the Semang people group who had migrated from the Malay Peninsula or Indochina (specifically Champa and Burma).
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Initially, the Mante people settled in Aceh Besar Regency and later began to spread to other regions.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Around the ninth and tenth century there was an influx of Arabian and Persian merchants to the Aceh region.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] When Marco Polo visited the area in 1292, he mentions that some of the port cities and towns had already converted to Islam.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] It is commonly thought that when the Samudera Pasai Sultanate was founded, Islam was fully established in the region.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Nonetheless, it is clear that Islam was a major religion in and around Aceh by the thirteenth century.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] During the decline of the Srivijaya kingdom, it is estimated that a number of Malay people began to migrate to Aceh.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] They then settled down in the valleys of Tamiang River and later became known as the Tamiang people.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] After they were conquered by the Samudera Pasai Sultanate kingdom (1330), only then did they begin to integrate into Acehnese society; although in terms of cultural and linguistic, there are still similarities with the Malay culture.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] By the sixteenth century, Aceh was an important cultural and scholastic Islamic center influential throughout much of Southeast Asia.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Most of the Minangkabau people who migrated to Aceh settled around Meulaboh and Krueng Seunagan valley.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Generally in these fertile areas they manage wet paddy fields and pepper farming, as well as some trading.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The mixed population of Acehnese-Minangkabau people is also found in the southern region, namely in the areas around Susoh, Tapaktuan and Labuhan Haji.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] There are many who converse daily in both Acehnese language and their own native dialect, the Aneuk Jamee language.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] As a result of the political expansion and diplomatic relations of the Aceh Sultanate with their surrounding region, the Acehnese people were also mixed with the Alas people, Gayonese, Karo people, Nias people and Kluet people.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The unification of the Acehnese culture that stemmed from various ancestry are primarily in the Acehnese language, religion of Islam and the local customs, as how it was formulated by Sultan Iskandar Muda in the *Adat Makuta Alam*laws, which is well known as "Kanun Mahkota Alam".
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] There are many of those who are of Indian descent in Aceh, which are closely linked to trading and the spreading of Hinduism-Buddhism and Islam in Aceh.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Those who are of Indian descent are mainly Tamils and Gujarati people which are found spread throughout the entire Aceh.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Among some of the Indian people's influence on the Acehnese people includes the cultural aspects and physical attributes of part of the Acehnese people, as well as the variety in Acehnese cuisine that frequently utilizes curry.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Numerous place names of Sanskrit origin (for example, Indrapuri, Aceh Besar) reflects the cultural heritage of Hinduism in the past.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Most of the Arabs that migrated to Aceh came from Hadhramaut, Yemen.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Among the immigrants are those of the Ba Alawi including al-Aydrus (Aidrus, Aydarus), al-Attas, al-Kathiri, Badjubier, Sungkar, Bawazier & al-Habsyi and other clans; all of which are Arabic clans that originated from Yemen.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] They came as ulamas to spread Islam and as traders.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Seunagan district for an instance, is well known to this today for numerous of ulamas of the Sayyid descent, of which the local community would address them with the title *Teungku Jet* or *Habib* as a form of respect.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Similarly, some of the Sultan of Aceh are also descendants of Sayyid.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Many of their descendants today have intermarried with the natives Acehnese people and do no longer bear their clan names.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] There are also those of Persian descent that generally came to spread religion and to trade, while those of Turkish descent generally were invited as ulamas, weapon merchants, military trainers and soldiers of war for the Aceh Sultanate.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] At present, people of Persian and Turkish descent in Indonesia are mostly scattered in Aceh Besar Regency.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Names of Persian and Turkish heritage are still being used by Acehnese people to name their children.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] In fact, the word *Banda* in the name of Banda Aceh city is also a word of Persian language in origin (*Banda* means "port").
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] People of Portuguese descent are found mainly in the Aceh Jaya Regency (northwest section of Aceh).
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Portuguese sailors under the lieutenant leadership of Captain Pinto, were sailing towards Malacca, stopped by and traded there; where some of them remained and settled there.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] History records that this event occurred between 1492 and 1511; of which at that time the area was under the rule of a small kingdom called Lamno, with King Meureuhom Daya as their ruler.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Until this day, some of their descendants can still be seen with European features.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Acehnese belongs to the Chamic languages, a branch of the Malayo-Polynesian languages from the Austronesian languages.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Languages that are closely related with Acehnese are Cham, Roglai, Jarai, Rade, Chru, Tsat, as well as other Chamic languages that are spoken in Cambodia, Vietnam and Hainan.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] There are also loanwords from Mon-Khmer languages, many of which are shared with other Chamic languages and had already been borrowed in the Proto-Chamic, the ancestral proto-language of all Chamic languages.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Vocabulary of the Acehnese language have been enriched by absorption from Sanskrit and Arabic language, especially in the field of religion, laws, governance, warfare, arts and knowledge.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] For centuries, the Acehnese language have also absorbed a lot from the Malay language.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Initially, a group of Chamic languages migrant speakers controlled a small region only, namely Banda Aceh in Aceh Besar Regency.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Marco Polo (1292) states that Aceh at that time consists of 8 smaller kingdoms, with each of them possessing their own language.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The expansion of power on other coastal kingdoms, especially Pidie, Pasai and Daya, and absorption of their population over time in a period of 400 years, eventually made the language of the Banda Aceh population became dominant in the coastal region of Aceh.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Other native languages speakers were then forced into the interior by the expansion of land for farming by the Acehnese language speakers.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Dialects of the Acehnese language that are found in the Aceh Besar Regency valley are divided into two major groups, namely the Tunong dialect for dialects in the highlands and Baroh dialect for dialects in the lowlands.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Most of the dialects that are used in Aceh Besar Regency and Daya, shows that settlements in that region have existed longer than any other regions.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] There are also many dialects in Pidie Regency, although not as much as in Aceh Besar Regency and Daya.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Dialects on the east coast of Pidie Regency and in southern Daya tend to be more homogeneous, so much so that it is co-related with the migration that came along with the expansion of power of the Aceh Sultanate after the 1500s.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Local government of Aceh, among others through Governor's Decree No.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] 2 of 1990 established the Institute of Acehnese Customary and Culture (Lembaga Adat dan Kebudayaan Aceh, LAKA), with the mandate to develop the customs and norms of the communities and customary institutions in Aceh.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Indirectly, this institution protects the preservation of the Acehnese language because in every cultural and customary activity, the delivery of such activities is carried out in the Acehnese language.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Likewise, the Acehnese language is also commonly used in everyday affairs that are organized by government agencies in Aceh.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Traditional Acehnese dance portrays the heritage culture, religion and folklore of the common folk.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Acehnese dance are generally performed in groups, either in a standing or sitting position, and the group of dancers are of the same gender.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] If seen from the musical standpoint, the dance can be grouped into two types.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] One is accompanied with vocals and physical percussive movements of the dancers themselves, and the other is simply accompanied by an assemble of musical instruments.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Acehnese cuisine is known for its combination of spices just as are commonly found in Indian and Arabic cuisine, such as ginger, pepper, coriander, cumin, cloves, cinnamon, cardamom and fennel.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] A variety of Acehnese food is cooked with curry or curry and coconut milk, which is generally combined with meat such as buffalo, beef, mutton, fish, or chicken.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Several types of traditional recipe use a blend of cannabis as a flavoring spice; such cases are also found in the cuisine of some other Southeast Asian countries, such as Laos.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] However today, those substances are no longer used.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Due to conflict after the Dutch invasion of Aceh, followed by Martial Law in Aceh during the attempt to break away from Indonesia, and the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake, many Acehnese fled abroad.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] The most significant number of Acehnese can be found in Malaysia and Scandinavian countries, especially Sweden and Norway countries.
[src:baduy-people/acehnese-people] Acehnese immigrants also can be found significantly in Australia, United States and Canada.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hinduism is the majority religion in the province of Bali, where approximately 86–87% of the population identify as Hindu, amounting to around 3.8 million adherents on the island.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Hinduism as practised in Bali accounts for the largest concentration of Hindus in Indonesia, a country where Hindus constitute about 1.7% of the total population.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hinduism emphasises ritual practice (orthopraxy) over doctrinal authority, communal religious obligation, ancestor veneration, and the maintenance of balance between the visible (*sekala*) and invisible (*niskala*) worlds.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] While it incorporates Hindu philosophical concepts such as *dharma*, *karma*, *punarjanman*, and *moksha*, these are interpreted through Balinese cosmology and social structures.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The religion also reflects historical syncretism with Buddhist and indigenous animist and ancestral worship traditions.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] In the modern period, Balinese Hinduism has been institutionally defined to meet Indonesian state requirements for religious recognition, including the articulation of a supreme divine principle, Sang Hyang Widhi Wasa.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] As such, Balinese Hinduism has been formally recognized by the Indonesian Government as one of the official religions practised in the country.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Despite these formal adaptations, Balinese Hinduism remains deeply rooted in temple-based worship, ritual cycles, and village institutions, and continues to play a central role in Balinese cultural and social life.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Prior to the introduction of Indian Hindu–Buddhist influences, religion in Bali was shaped by indigenous Austronesian traditions centred on ancestor veneration, animism, and sacred landscapes.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] These beliefs were not displaced by Hinduism but were incorporated into it, remaining most evident in the Hindu practices of the Bali Aga communities today.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This continuity is exemplified at the temple Pura Pucak Penulisan where squatting ancestral statues have been dated to 2,000 years old and have remained sacred across both pre-Hindu and Hindu periods.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Hindu and Buddhist concepts entered the Indonesian archipelago as early as the first century CE through long-distance trade and cultural exchange.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Archeological evidence of Indian trade with Bali has been found at Sembiran village dating to this period.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Stories from the *Mahabharata* have been traced in the Indonesian islands from the first century CE with these versions mirroring those found in Tamil Nadu.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] These influences arrived into Bali primarily via Java rather than directly from India and were mediated through local courts and religious specialists.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Sanskrit terminology, Indian epics, cosmology, and ritual ideas were selectively adopted and adapted to existing Balinese frameworks.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] According to Balinese legend and recorded on *lontar* manuscripts, Hinduism was founded on the island by the East Indian priest Rsi Markandeya in the 8th century CE during the period of the Mataram Kingdom on Java.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Markandeya led an early expedition to Bali with his followers, which was unsuccessful due to a widespread disease outbreak, most likely cholera.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Following this setback, he returned to Java.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Through spiritual reflection and the application of knowledge associated with Atharva Vedic traditions and *Rasa Shastra*, Markandeya developed a ritual method of water purification.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] He subsequently returned to Bali, where he is said to have sanctified the island’s water sources by burying the *Panca Dhatu* (five sacred metals) at designated locations on Mount Agung and founded temples across the island including the mother temple, Besakih.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The most significant formative period for Balinese Hinduism occurred during and after the decline of the Javanese **Majapahit** empire in the late 14th and 15th centuries.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] In 1343 the Majaphit led by Prime Minister Gajah Mada conquered Bali defeating the local ruler at Bedulu.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This pivotal invasion transformed Bali into a vassal state, resulting in a significant influx of Javanese Hindu culture, aristocracy, and artistry, which deeply influenced Balinese society, language, and religion for centuries.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] As Islamic polities rose in Java during the late 15th century, Hindu-Javanese elites, priests, artists, and intellectuals migrated to Bali.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] They brought court culture, Old Javanese (*Kawi*) literature, temple architecture, and Brahmanical ritual traditions.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] As was the case in Java, Budhism in Bali was largely integrated into a dominant Hindu religion.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The most significant figure during this period was the priest Dang Hyang Nirartha who is credited with being the most influential reformer of Balinese Hinduism.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] He was sent to Bali by the Majapahit court in 1492 and founded the Sahivite priesthood that is now ubiquitous.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Niratha was an important promoter of the idea of *moksha* (freedom from the cycle of death and rebirth) and introduced into Balinese temples the *padmasana* shrine of the empty throne as an altar to the supreme god Acintya or Shiva.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The temples on the coasts of Bali were augmented with the *padmasana* shrines by the dozen during Nirartha's travels.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] During the Dutch colonial rule in the 19th and early 20th centuries, Balinese religion was increasingly categorised and studied through European frameworks.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Colonial administrators and scholars often described Balinese Hinduism as a "preserved" or "classical" form of Hinduism, a characterisation that obscured its dynamic and adaptive nature.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Colonial intervention disrupted royal authority and temple patronage but did not dismantle village-based religious institutions, which remained central to religious continuity.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Following the Indonesian independence, Balinese religious leaders undertook a process of formal reinterpretation to secure official recognition of their religion within the Indonesian state, which requires belief in a supreme deity.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This led to the articulation of Ida Sang Hyang Widhi Wasa as the supreme divine principle and the formal naming of the religion as *Agama Hindu Dharma*.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] In 1952, the Indonesian Ministry of Religion came under the control of Islamists who severely constrained the acceptable definition of a "religion".
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] To be acceptable as an officially government recognised religion, the ministry defined "religion" as one that is monotheistic, has codified religious law, possesses a prophet and a Holy Book, amongst other requirements.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hindus were declared as "people without a religion", and available to be converted.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The Balinese disagreed, debated, adapted, and declared their form of Hinduism to be monotheistic, and presented it in a form to be eligible for the status of *agama* under the 1952 amended articles.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] To accomplish this, the Balinese initiated a series of student and cultural exchange initiatives between Bali and India to help formulate the core principles behind Balinese Hinduism (Vedas, Upanishad, Puranas, Itihasa).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This led to the joint petition of 1958 which demanded the Indonesian government recognize Hindu Dharma.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The petition's focus on the "undivided one" was to satisfy the constitutional requirement that Indonesian citizens have a monotheistic belief in one God with Ida Sanghyang Widhi Wasa being identified as the undivided one.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] In the Balinese language, this term has two meanings: "the Divine ruler of the Universe" and "the Divine Absolute Cosmic Law".
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This creative phrase met the monotheistic requirement of the Indonesian Ministry of Religion in the former sense, while the latter sense of its meaning preserved the central ideas of dharma in ancient scripts of Hinduism.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Bali became the only part of Indonesia to remain predominantly Hindu.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The foundation of Balinese Hinduism rests on three principles: *Tattwa* (Philosophy), *Susila* (Ethics), and *Acara* (Ritual Practice).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] These principles are inseparable, forming a unified whole.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hindu philosophy emphasizes the pursuit of ultimate truth, attainable through three means of knowledge (*Tri Pramana*): *Pratyaksa Pramana* (direct observation), *Anumana Pramana* (inference), and *Agama Pramana* (study of scripture and guidance from trusted teachers).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] (left), the Divine Oneness and supreme god of Balinese Hinduism.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hinduism recognises a supreme, formless reality known as **Sang Hyang Widhi Wasa**, understood as the ultimate source of existence.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This supreme principle is manifested through multiple gods (*dewa*), each representing specific aspects of cosmic function and natural order.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Sang Hyang Widhi has been likened to the concept of the Christian God or Allah in Islam.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The major Hindu deities—such as Brahma, Vishnu, and Shiva—are revered, with Shiva often occupying a particularly prominent role.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Divinity is not viewed as distant or abstract but as actively present in the natural world, temples, ancestors, and daily life.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hinduism shares core Hindu concepts of ***karma***, ***samsara*** (the cycle of birth, death, and rebirth), and ***moksha*** (liberation).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Actions in this life influence one’s future rebirths, shaping both individual destiny and family lineage.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Liberation is understood not only as spiritual release but also as the purification of the soul through ethical conduct, ritual observance, and devotion across multiple lifetimes.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] A central philosophical concept in Balinese Hinduism is ***Tri Hita Karana***, meaning "the three causes of well-being".
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This principle underpins religious practice, social organisation, architecture, agriculture, and environmental stewardship in Balinese life.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hindu Ethics or ***susila*** *e*mphasize harmonious relationships with others and the universe, grounded in sincerity, sacrifice (*yadnya*), and compassion.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The word *susila* comes from "Su" (good, harmonious) and "Sila" (conduct).The principal *Tat Twam Asi* ("He is you") teaches that harming others is harming oneself, while helping others is helping oneself.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Ethics are reinforced by *Tri Kaya Parisudha*—thinking good (*manacika*)*, s*peaking good (*wacika*), *a*nd doing good (*kayika)*.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Ethics are strongly grounded in the concept of ***dharma***, understood as the proper fulfilment of religious, social, and communal obligations rather than adherence to a codified moral law.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Ethical conduct is expressed primarily through participation in ritual life, maintenance of social harmony, and fulfilment of responsibilities within family, village, and religious institutions.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Moral behaviour is therefore relational and situational, embedded in collective practice rather than individual belief alone.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] In Balinese society, individuals are expected to contribute labour, resources, and time to their ***banjar*** (neighbourhood association), ***desa adat*** (customary village), and temple networks.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Participation in rituals, festivals, and collective work (*gotong royong*) is both a religious and ethical obligation.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Failure to fulfil communal duties is viewed less as a personal moral failing than as a disruption of social and cosmic balance.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Sanctions for ethical lapses are typically social—such as loss of standing or ritual exclusion—rather than punitive in a legal sense.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Ethical behaviour in Balinese Hinduism includes proper recognition of social roles, seniority, and ritual status.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Respect for elders, religious specialists, and community leaders is considered a moral duty, reflected in language use, bodily comportment, and ritual etiquette.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Correct ritual performance (*tata susila* and *tata upacara*) is central to ethical life.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Ritual errors are not necessarily viewed as sins but as technical or procedural failures that may require correction through additional offerings or ceremonies.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Intention (*niat*) and sincerity are valued, but ethical emphasis remains on correct participation rather than internal belief alone.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This reflects a broader orientation toward orthopraxy (right practice) rather than orthodoxy (right belief).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Ethical responsibility in Balinese Hinduism extends to the natural environment, consistent with the principle of **Tri Hita Karana**.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Humans are expected to maintain respectful and sustainable relationships with land, water, and animals, which are regarded as spiritually animated.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Agricultural practices, temple calendars, and water management systems such as ***subak*** reflect ethical commitments to cooperation, fairness, and ecological balance.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hindu ethics incorporate the principle of ***karma***, whereby actions generate consequences that may unfold across multiple lifetimes.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] However, karma is not interpreted strictly as individual moral reward or punishment.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] It is also understood as collective and ancestral, linking families and communities across generations.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Ethical conduct therefore includes maintaining ancestral obligations, performing rites correctly, and preserving family and temple continuity, as these actions are believed to influence both present harmony and future rebirth.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Through the ages, the Balinese have adopted the Indian Hindu pantheon of gods (dewa) and goddesses (dewi), though having adapted it to their own history, character and unique needs.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] I Nyoman Tantrayana argues that, while the concept of a supreme god remained largely unmanifest in Indian Hinduism, in Bali it became personified as the enigmatic Sanghyang Widhi Wasa, and that the pantheon of gods are manifestations of the supreme consciousness.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] He contends that this system of worship is not truly pantheistic, but rather represents a flexible form of monotheism.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] According to Tantrayana, these gods and the associated Balinese mythology assists in personalising the relationship to the divine.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The major Indian Hindu gods of the ***Trimurti*** —**Brahma**, **Wisnu** (Vishnu**)**, and **Çiwa** (Shiva)—hold particular significance to the Balinese, with Shiva often occupying a central position in Balinese theology as a god of transformation and spiritual power.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] In Balinese Hindu texts, the alternate tripartite concept of Shiva of Indian Shaivism is also found.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This is usually referred in Balinese as "*Siwa-Sadasiwa-Paramasiwa*", where Shiva is the creator, the maintainer and the destroyer of cyclic existence.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Along with the *trimurti,* Balinese Hindus worship a range of gods and goddesses (variously referred to as *Hyang, Dewata* and *Batara-Batari*), as well as others that are unique and not found in Indian Hinduism.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Among deities associated with the natural world, those linked to mountains and lakes are considered the most powerful.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The god of Mount Agung, **Ida Bhatara Gunung Agung**, is honoured at Besakih Temple and in *meru* shrines throughout the island.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] **Dewi Ulun Danu Batur**, the goddess of Lake Batur, is associated with water, fertility, and agricultural prosperity.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The sea occupies a contrasting position in Balinese cosmology.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] It is regarded simultaneously as a source of danger and a powerful agent of purification.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Rather than personifying a single sea deity, the Balinese commonly refer to ***Segara***, meaning "the sea" itself, as a potent and impersonal sacred force.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Among the most intimate and personally significant divine beings are deified ancestors.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The relationship between the Balinese and their ancestors is both reverent and practical: the souls of the dead are believed to attain full absorption into the heavenly realm only through purification rites performed by the living.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] In return, ancestors may bestow protection, blessings, and guidance, sometimes communicating through trance mediums.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The term ***Bhatara Kawitan*** refers to the original ancestor of a clan, who is worshipped at family temples and regarded as the spiritual origin of the lineage.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Ancestor worship thus forms a central link between domestic ritual life and the wider Balinese cosmological order.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Deceased family members are believed to remain spiritually present and capable of influencing the living.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Proper rituals ensure their peaceful transition and continued protection of descendants.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Major ceremonies, particularly cremation (*ngaben*), are essential for releasing the soul and enabling reincarnation or spiritual ascent.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Ancestors are honoured in family shrines and temples alongside deities.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Ancient kings are also regarded as influential deities in Balinese religion and are believed, on occasion, to manifest during temple anniversary celebrations (*odalan*), with the manner of their appearance varying in dignity and form.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hinduism recognises an inseparable relationship between the **seen** (*sekala*) and **unseen** (*niskala*) worlds.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Spirits, deities, and forces of chaos coexist with humans and must be acknowledged through offerings, rituals, and ethical behaviour.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Not all spiritual forces are benevolent; rituals aim to maintain equilibrium between constructive and destructive energies rather than eliminate one entirely.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This relationship is not expressed solely through formal ritual but is also demonstrated in Balinese performing arts.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] **Shadow puppet theatre (*wayang kulit*)** and the **Barong dance** symbolically enact the interaction between order and chaos, good and destructive forces, and the visible and invisible worlds.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hindu belief assigns spiritual significance to direction and space, reflecting a cosmological order that structures religious life and the built environment.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Mountains—particularly Mount Agung—are regarded as sacred abodes of the gods, while the sea is associated with powerful and potentially chaotic forces.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This opposition is commonly expressed through the spatial concepts of ***kaja*** (towards the mountains, sacred) and ***kelod*** (towards the sea, less sacred).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Temples, homes, villages, and even seating arrangements are organised according to these spatial principles.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Sacred spaces are oriented *kaja*-ward, while activities associated with everyday or impure functions are placed *kelod*-ward.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] These principles are integrated into the system of ***Dewata Nawa Sanga***, the "nine guardian deities," who preside over the eight cardinal and intercardinal directions and the centre.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Each direction is associated with a specific deity, colour, and spiritual quality, together forming a protective cosmic grid that maintains balance and order.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hinduism does not rely on a single canonical scripture.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Instead, religious knowledge is drawn from a diverse body of Sanskrit-derived Hindu texts, Old Javanese (*Kawi*) literature, local ritual manuals, and oral tradition.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Sacred texts function primarily as guides for rather than as sources of fixed doctrine.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hinduism utilises palm leaf manuscripts (lontar) to record religious scripture, ritual practice, cosmology, and ethics.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The refined technique of engraving words in Balinese script on processed palm-leaves originates from pre-modern India and is still practiced on Bali today.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Traditionally, **lontar** manuscripts were kept and transmitted by Brahmanical and aristocratic elites, religious and ritual specialists, folk healers (*balian*), and educated commoners.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The largest collections are found in Brahmanical households and former royal palaces, but many ordinary families—particularly in northern and eastern Bali—also possess a small number of lontar.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] One estimate suggests that Bali alone may contain tens of thousands of these manuscripts.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Classical Hindu texts such as the **Vedas**, **Upanishads**, **Mahabharata**, **Ramayana**, and **Puranas** are recognised as authoritative in principle, but they are generally known through summaries, commentaries, and adaptations rather than direct textual study.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Old Javanese literary works play a particularly important role in Balinese Hinduism.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Texts such as the *kakawin* and *kidung*—poetic compositions based on Indian epics and local mythology—form a central part of religious education, temple performance, and moral instruction.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] In the modern period, Balinese Hindu institutions have produced standardised interpretations of scripture to align religious teaching with national educational frameworks.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Ritual life is structured around a complex ceremonial calendar combining the 210-day **Pawukon** cycle and the lunar **Saka** calendar.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Ceremonies mark temple anniversaries (*odalan*), agricultural cycles, lifecycle events, and communal purification rites.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Major rituals involve the cooperation of extended families, neighbourhood associations (*banjar*), and temple communities.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Offerings, known as ***banten***, are a central element of Balinese religious life.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] They are prepared to give pleasure to both gods and spirits and are believed to generate good *karma* for those involved in their making.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Family shrines receive offerings daily, typically in the morning and again in the late afternoon.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] On important ritual days—such as *Kajeng–Keliwon*, *Tilem*, *Purnama*, the *Tumpeks*, *Galungan*, and other festivals—more elaborate offerings are prepared.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Offerings in the form of *canang sari* are usually presented by a female member of the household, who must be dressed in proper Balinese ceremonial attire.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] They are carried on a tray together with a burning incense stick, and the essence of the offering is gently wafted toward the shrine.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Before eating or drinking, many Balinese households prepare coffee with a small sweet and offer it to Sang Hyang Widhi Wasa at the family house temples, accompanied by incense.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] When rice is first cooked each day, a small portion is set aside on small squares of banana leaf and lightly sprinkled with salt.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Commonly numbering between fifteen and twenty, these simple offerings are distributed to key ritual points throughout the family compound, including the kitchen, household shrines, wells or water connections, and entrances or pathways.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] For major ceremonies and temple festivals, larger offerings (*banten gede*) are prepared and taken in procession to temples.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] These elaborate offerings include cooked foods (rice dishes, cakes, fruit, meat), extensive flower arrangements, incense, and ritual objects arranged in complex palm-leaf structures.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] At certain rites—such as *odalan* and major calendrical ceremonies—animal sacrifice (most commonly chickens, ducks, or pigs) may be included, prepared according to strict ritual rules.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Daily prayer in Bali is anchored by *Tri Sandhya*, a formal prayer recited three times a day.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] It is rarely recited by Balinese daily and is often broadcast over temple loudspeakers, sometimes mistaken by foreigners for the Muslim call to prayer.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Tri Sandhya is also recited by students in schools, reinforcing its role as a shared civic and religious practice.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Men sit cross-legged in *padmasana*, while women sit in the heel position (*bajrasana*).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] In schools, prayer is usually performed standing (*pada asana*).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] When reciting prayers, the hands are cupped like a lotus flower at the chest, symbolising purity and offering.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Tri Sandhya is recited at ceremonies, though it may be omitted due to its length when ritual schedules are tight.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Ceremonial worship centres on *Kramaning Sembah.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Krama* means manners and *Sembah* means appreciation.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] It is also known as Panca Sembah ("five worships").
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This structured sequence involves praying to Sang Hyang Widhi five times.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The hands are raised to the head as mantras are recited; then raised again holding a flower, with mantras repeated three times, followed by a final repetition without a flower.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The hands remain lifted for as long as the priest rings the bell (*genta*), marking the climax of the prayer.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] At the conclusion, worshippers receive holy water (*tirtha*): it is sprinkled by the priest (pemangku) three times, then received in the right hand and drunk three times, followed by splashing it onto the forehead three times.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Finally, water-soaked rice (*bija*) is given—a few grains are eaten, and the remainder pressed onto the forehead.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Temples (*pura*) are the central institutions of religious life in Balinese Hinduism.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Bali is home to tens of thousands of temples**,** commonly estimated at over 20,000, ranging from small family shrines and neighbourhood temples to major regional and island-wide sanctuaries.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese temples are organised according to sacred spatial principles that reflect cosmic order and direction, and are dedicated to specific deities, ancestral lineages, natural forces, or communal functions.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Every level of social organisation—family, clan, village, irrigation association (*subak*), and kingdom—maintains its own temples, each with distinct ritual obligations.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Temple worship is communal rather than congregational.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Individuals participate as members of families, villages, or ritual groups, with temple festivals (*odalan*) structured around collective responsibility rather than individual devotion.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Purification rites are fundamental to Balinese Hindu practice, which is often referred to as ***Agama Tirtha*** ("the religion of holy water").
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Holy water (*tirtha*) is regarded as a primary medium of divine power and accompanies every act of Balinese Hindu worship where it is believed to "cleanse spiritual impurities, fend off evil forces, and render the recipient immune to the attacks of negative or demonic influences".
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The High Balinese word for water *tirtha* and Middle Balinese *toya* are used to distinguish holy water from ordinary water which is called *yeh* using Low Balinese.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Holy water is created by priests every morning by reciting mantras and the use of ritual hand gestures (*mudras*).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Whilst all holy water is considered sacred, some holy water is considered more powerful.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Water derived from sacred places or created through the use of more powerful *mantras* is believed to contain more mystic energy.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Holy water used in every day temple worship may not come from as significant a source high in the mountains as what may be required for water used for important rites such as a temple ceremony or cremation.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Priests and ritual specialists hold a central position in Balinese Hinduism, guiding religious practice to maintain social order and cosmic balance.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Broadly, ritual specialists are organised into two hierarchical categories—*Dwijati* ("twice-born") and *Ekajati* ("once-born")—within which three functional roles are commonly distinguished: ***pedanda*** (high priests), **pemangku** (temple priests), and **balian** (ritual healers and mediums).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The ***Golongan Dwijati*** comprises the highest-ranking priests.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Following extensive training, candidates undergo a major purification ceremony symbolising a second birth, from which the term *dwijati* derives.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This group includes titles such as *Rsi, Empu, Pandita, Sulinggih, Pedanda, Bujangga, Dukuh, Bhagawan,* and *Dang Hyang*, with *pedanda* commonly used as an umbrella term.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Pedanda are not usually attached to a single temple but serve communities connected to them through lineage or tradition.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Their responsibilities include preparing the most ritually potent holy water (*tirta*) for major temple festivals and officiating key life-cycle rites such as tooth filing and cremation.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] In ritual performance they employ sacred gestures (*mudra*) and mantras.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Most are **pedanda Siwa**, following Shaivite traditions, while a smaller number are ***pedanda Buda***, drawing on Buddhist textual and ritual lineages; some ceremonies require priests of both types to officiate together.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The ***Golongan Ekajati*** encompasses other ritual specialists who undergo a lesser purification.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This group includes *pemangku, pinandita, wasi, mangku, balian, mangku dalang, pengeman,* and *dang acarya*, with *pemangku* often used as a general term.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Pemangku are temple priests responsible for daily and periodic rituals.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Dressed in white and drawn from any caste other than Brahman, they consecrate offerings, prepare holy water, and lead temple ceremonies.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] When dressed in full ceremonial attire, the body is symbolically divided into three parts.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] For men, the ***kamen*** (sarong) and ***saput*** (outer cloth) cover the lower body, while the ***udeng*** (headcloth) separates the head from the body.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This division reflects the Balinese three-level conception of the universe: *bhurloka* (lower realm), *bhuwah* (human world), and *suarga* (heavenly realm).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The *udeng*, worn daily by Balinese men, has defined philosophical meaning.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The right fold must be higher than the left, symbolising the supremacy of *dharma* (righteous conduct) over *adharma* (unrighteous conduct).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The knot is placed at the centre of the forehead, representing the focus and origin of the mind, while the upward edge signifies concentration directed toward the divine.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The udeng is also interpreted as embodying the *Tri Murti*, with its folds symbolically associated with Brahma, Vishnu, and Shiva.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Women customarily wear a ***kamen*** wrapped tightly around the lower body, a ***kebaya*** (fitted blouse) covering the upper body and shoulders, and a ***selendang*** (sash) tied at the waist.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] As with men, the sash carries symbolic meaning, representing self-restraint and the ordering of the body during worship.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Hair is typically tied up or neatly arranged, and shoulders and legs must be covered.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Colours are generally modest—most commonly white or yellow—signifying ritual purity, though variations may occur for specific ceremonies or temple anniversaries (*odalan*).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Darker and brighter colours are worn for weddings, and even darker colours are preferred at cremations (*ngadben*).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Performance is central to Balinese Hinduism and is understood primarily as ritual offering rather than entertainment.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Dance, music, and shadow theatre are integral to temple festivals, rites of passage, and calendrical ceremonies, where they serve to honour the gods, maintain cosmic balance (*dharma*), and protect the community.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese dance is closely tied to ritual context and is traditionally classified as sacred (*wali*), ceremonial (*bebali*), or entertainment (*balih-balihan*), with sacred and ceremonial forms performed within temple precincts as offerings.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Musical accompaniment is provided by gamelan ensembles, whose interlocking rhythms structure ritual time and accompany dance and drama.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hinduism places strong emphasis on rites of passage, including birth rituals, tooth-filing (*metatah*), marriage, and cremation (*ngaben*).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] These ceremonies mark transitions in spiritual and social status and are essential for maintaining harmony between the individual, family, ancestors, and the wider community.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] There are a total of thirteen ceremonies concerned with life from conception until, but not including, death, each of which has four elements: placation of evil spirits, purification with holy water, wafting of the essence, and prayer.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] These ceremonies mark major events in a person's life, including birth, puberty, grain feeding, and marriage.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] A newborn baby is believed to represent the soul of an ancestor and is regarded as a god for the first 42 days of its life.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] However, the mother is regarded as impure and is not allowed to participate in any religious activities during this period.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] A baby must not touch the impure ground until it is 105 days old, halfway to the celebration of its first birthday according to the 210-day Balinese *Pawukon* calendar.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Once it reaches its first birthday, the child's family will celebrate the *Otonan* birthday ceremony.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Once the child reaches puberty, the six upper canine teeth are filed until they are even.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The most important ceremonies take place after death and result in the soul being freed to be eventually reincarnated (*samsara*).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Unlike the death rites of other religions, the physical body is not the focus, as it is seen as nothing more than a temporary container of the soul and fit only for expedient disposal.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] In fact, the body must be burned before the soul can leave it completely.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The Balinese cremation ceremony (*ngaben*) to bring this about can be extremely expensive because an elaborate ceremony is a way of showing respect for a soul destined to become a god with considerable powers over those left behind.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Therefore, bodies are sometimes temporarily buried until the family can accumulate enough funds for cremation, although the bodies of priests or high-class families are preserved above ground.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hinduism does not prescribe a single, universal dietary code.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Dietary practice has historically been shaped by ritual context, social status, and local custom rather than by permanent religious prohibitions comparable to those found in some other traditions.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Historically, dietary distinctions existed between caste groups (wangsa), particularly in relation to ritual purity and social etiquette.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Higher-status groups, especially Brahmana households, often observed stricter dietary practices, including avoidance of certain meats or foods such as beef or abstaining from alcohol.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] In the past, Balinese were said to be forbidden from consuming flesh of human, cat, monkey, dog, crocodile, mouse, snake, frog, certain poisonous fish, leech, stinging insect, crow, eagle, owl, or any other bird of prey.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Priests and ritual specialists traditionally follow more regulated dietary discipline during consecration, fasting, or purification periods.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Such restrictions are situational and temporary, intended to maintain ritual balance rather than moral purity.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The most important festival is *Galungan* (related to Deepavali), a celebration of the triumph of *dharma* over *adharma*.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] It is calculated according to the 210-day Balinese *Pawukon* calendar and takes place on the Wednesday (*Buda*) of the eleventh week (*Dunggulan*).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] According to tradition, the spirits of the dead descend from Heaven, to return ten days later on *Kuningan*.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The fourth day of the year is called *Pagerwesi*, meaning "iron fence".
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] It commemorates a battle between good and evil.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The Hindu festival of Maha Shivaratri is celebrated by Balinese Hindus as Siwa Ratri.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hinduism has traditionally recognised a system of social classification known as *wangsa* or *varna*, shaped by indigenous Balinese social organisation and later Hindu-Javanese influence.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] While it uses Sanskrit-derived terminology, the Balinese system differs from Indian caste systems in that it has never functioned as a rigid hierarchy based on occupation or ritual purity.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Caste affiliation is most visibly expressed through personal names and titles and historically influenced levels of speech in the Balinese language.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Inter-caste marriage has long occurred and has never been absolutely prohibited.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Since the 20th century, caste distinctions in Bali have declined in social and legal importance.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Reformist interpretations of Hinduism emphasise vocation and religious practice over inherited status, expanding access to priesthood and diminishing caste as a determinant of social position.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Today, caste functions largely as a cultural and historical identity marker within Balinese Hinduism.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hinduism is formally regulated and administered through a combination of Indonesian state institutions and Balinese religious and customary authorities.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] This dual system reflects Indonesia’s constitutional framework for recognised religions alongside Bali’s long-standing system of customary law (*adat*).
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] At the national level, Balinese Hinduism is recognised as an official religion of Indonesia under the name *Agama Hindu Dharma*.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Oversight is exercised by the **Ministry of Religious Affairs** (*Kementerian Agama*), which is responsible for religious education, registration of religious officials, state-recognised ceremonies, and the administration of religious affairs across all recognised faiths.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Hindu religious education in public schools and universities, as well as the certification of Hindu teachers and clergy, falls under this ministry.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Religious doctrine, ritual standards, and theological interpretation are primarily guided by the **Parisada Hindu Dharma Indonesia** (PHDI), the national Hindu council.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] PHDI serves as the principal representative body for Hindus in Indonesia and plays a central role in defining theology, issuing religious guidance, standardising ritual practice, and representing Hindu interests to the state.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] It has been instrumental in articulating key concepts such as **Sang Hyang Widhi Wasa** to meet national requirements for monotheistic belief.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] At the provincial and local level in Bali, religious life is closely intertwined with customary governance.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The **Majelis Desa Adat** coordinates and oversees **desa adat** (customary villages), which are responsible for temple management, ritual calendars, community obligations, and the enforcement of customary religious norms.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] While *desa adat* operate independently of the state administrative village system (*desa dinas*), they are formally recognised under Balinese provincial law.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Temples (*pura*) are administered locally by temple councils and village institutions, with ritual authority exercised by priests (*pedanda*, *pemangku*) operating within frameworks recognised by both PHDI and local customary bodies.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] In practice, governance of Balinese Hinduism relies on cooperation between state regulation, religious councils, and customary institutions rather than centralised control.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Balinese Hindus built Pura Parahyangan Agung Jagatkarta, the second largest temple in Indonesia after Pura Besakih in Bali, dedicated to Hindu Sundanese King Sri Baduga Maharaja Sang Ratu Jaya Dewata Prabu Siliwangi.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Pura Aditya Jaya is the largest temple in Indonesian capital Jakarta.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] At least four Balinese Hindu temples exist in Europe.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] A padmasana exists in Hamburg, Germany in front of the Museum of Ethnology, Hamburg.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Pura Girinatha in Dili, Timor Leste, was built by Indonesian immigrants.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] The recently constructed Pura Tri Hita Karana is located in Erholungspark Marzahn park in Berlin, Germany.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] Two temples exist in the Pairi Daiza botanical garden in Belgium.
[src:baduy-people/agama-hindu-dharma] A temple was inaugurated in May 2025 in Kallenkote, Indonesia.
[src:baduy-people/airoran-people] The **Airoran people** are an ethnic group of the Banso peoples, inhabiting the western region of the Apauwar River, including parts of Sarmi Regency, Indonesia.
[src:baduy-people/airoran-people] They speak various languages including Airoran and Sasawa, all of which belong to the Airoran language family.
[src:baduy-people/airoran-people] The Airoran people originally lived along the Apauwar River and in the hills between the river and Lake Rombebai.
[src:baduy-people/airoran-people] Recently, one group was relocated to the coast at the mouth of the Apauwar River.
[src:baduy-people/airoran-people] However, the people still depend on the hinterland for their food and livelihood.
[src:baduy-people/airoran-people] The residents of Subu, one of Airoran's villages, have very positive feelings towards outsiders because of their experiences in the mid-1970s with the Hurd family who lived there.
[src:baduy-people/airoran-people] The Airoran residential area can be reached by motorboat from the town of Sarmi in about six hours.
[src:baduy-people/airoran-people] It's a three-day walking trip from Sarmi, but walking seems to be the common way to get there, this is the coastal village of Subu at the mouth of the Apauwar River.
[src:baduy-people/airoran-people] Inland villages can also be reached from Subu by canoe or from the Aurimi airstrip in the Kwerba area, a week-long journey down the Apauwar River.
[src:baduy-people/airoran-people] The most recent population estimate for the Airoran people is 400 (De Vries, 1991), but this figure may be an underestimate.
[src:baduy-people/airoran-people] The Airoran people has three main villages, but there appears to be a large number of people who do not live in villages.
[src:baduy-people/airoran-people] The number of Airoran people likely ranges from 700 to 1,000.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera is known for its in-depth and frontline reporting particularly in conflict zones such as the Arab Spring, the Gaza–Israel conflict and others.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera's coverage of the Arab Spring won the network numerous awards, including the Peabody Award.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] It positions itself as an alternative media platform to the dominance of Western media outlets like CNN and BBC, focusing on narrative reporting where subjects present their own stories.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The channel launched on 15 November 2006 with an investment of approximately $1 billion from the Qatari government.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Initially slated to be named Al Jazeera International, the channel was renamed nine months prior to the launch.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] This decision was influenced by one of the channel's backers, who argued that the original Arabic-language channel already encompassed an international scope.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The channel was expected to reach approximately 40 million households, but it significantly surpassed this launch target, reaching 80 million homes.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] By 2009, the service was accessible in every major European market and available to 130 million homes across more than 100 countries through cable and satellite, according to a network spokeswoman in Washington.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] However, the channel had limited penetration in the American market, where it was carried by only one satellite service and a handful of cable networks.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English subsequently launched a campaign to enter the North American market, including a dedicated website.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] In August 2011, it became available to some cable subscribers in New York, having previously been an option for some viewers in Washington, D.C., Ohio, and Los Angeles.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The channel primarily reached the United States through its live online streaming service.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Following approval from the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission on 26 November 2009, Al Jazeera English became readily available on most major Canadian television providers, including Rogers and Bell Satellite TV.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English and Iran's state-run Press TV were the only international English-language television broadcasters with journalists reporting from inside both Gaza and Israel during the 2008–2009 Israel-Gaza conflict.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Foreign press access to Gaza was limited via either Egypt or Israel.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] However, Al Jazeera's reporters Ayman Mohyeldin and Sherine Tadros were already inside Gaza when the conflict began.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The network encourages online viewing at its own website or via its channel on YouTube.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English HD launched in the United Kingdom on Freeview on 26 November 2013, and began streaming in HD on YouTube in 2015.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] On 1 January 2020, Al Jazeera English debuted a new graphics package to coincide with the renovation of its main Doha studio, the last of the channel's three main studios (Doha, London, and Washington D.C.) to be upgraded since the channel's launch in 2006.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] On 3 January 2013, Al Jazeera Media Network announced that it had purchased Current TV in the United States and would launch an American news channel.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Sixty percent of the channel's programming would be produced in the United States, while 40% would be from Al Jazeera English.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] This was later changed at the request of pay-television providers to almost 100% US programming.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] However, Al Jazeera America maintained a close working relationship with Al Jazeera English.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The channel aired *Newshour* in the morning and midday hours, and cut to live Al Jazeera English coverage of large breaking international news stories outside those hours.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The Al Jazeera English programmes *Witness*, *Earthrise*, *The Listening Post*, *Talk To Al Jazeera*, *Al Jazeera Correspondent* and *101 East* along with *Al Jazeera Investigates* aired regularly on Al Jazeera America.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] On 13 January 2016, Al Jazeera America announced that the network would shut down on 12 April 2016, citing the "economic landscape".
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] In 2013, Al Jazeera Media Network began planning a new channel called *Al Jazeera UK*; the British channel was set to broadcast for five hours during prime time as a local opt-out of Al Jazeera English.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Ultimately, the planned UK channel never materialised.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English continued to broadcast some of its daily bulletins from London until July 2023, when it moved its base to Qatar.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The channel is available in many countries, mostly via satellite, sometimes via cable.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English provides a free HD stream on its website for unlimited viewing.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera news segments were frequently included on the American public television program Worldfocus which aired from 6 October 2008 until 2 April 2010.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera can also be streamed on any iOS or Android device with an internet connection using a free application.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English is also available on connected TV and OTT streaming services like Pluto TV and Haystack News.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Along with a free unlimited high-quality stream on the official Al Jazeera English website, Online subscriptions allowing unlimited viewing may be purchased from Jump TV, RealPlayer, and VDC.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Headlines from Al Jazeera English are available on Twitter.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English's website also contains news reports and full episodes of their programs that can be viewed for free on their website.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The videos are hosted by YouTube, where viewers can also go to find the videos.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English is available in the UK and Ireland on Freeview channel 235, Sky channel 511, Freesat channel 203 and Virgin Media channel 622.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] A notice appearing on Freeview channel 235 indicates that Al Jazeera is scheduled to end there on 30 September 2024 but that its service will remain on channel 251 as a streaming service for STBs that support streaming.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The channel initially began test streaming Al Jazeera English (then called "Al Jazeera International") in March 2006 on Hot Bird, Astra 1E, Hispasat, AsiaSat3S, Eutelsat 28A and Panamsat PAS 10.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Telenors Thor, Türksat and Eutelsat 25A were added to the satellites carrying it.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Eutelsat 28A carried the test stream on frequency 11.681 under the name "AJI".
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English is available in Sub-Saharan Africa mainly via DStv and StarTimes' satellite and terrestrial TV platforms.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] It is also available FTA on satellites like Belintersat 51.5°E and Nilesat 201.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] In Northern Africa, Al Jazeera English is available on telcos like Etisalat.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] It is also available via satellite, on Badr°26E and various local cable operators.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] In New Zealand, Al Jazeera English is available 24 hours a day on Freeview (New Zealand) channel 16 and Sky (New Zealand) channel 90.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] From October 2013, Freeview (New Zealand) broadcast on the Kordia operated free-to-air DVB-T terrestrial network.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Prior to the December 2012 analog switchoff Triangle TV re-broadcast various Al Jazeera programmes in Auckland on its free-to-air UHF channel.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] TV One was going to replace BBC World News with this service during their off-air hours of 01:30 to 06:00 from 1 April 2013, however opted to run infomercials instead.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] In April 2010, Al Jazeera English was taken off air in Singapore Singtel TV with unspecified reasons, according to the official Al Jazeera English website.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] On 7 December 2010, Al Jazeera said its English language service has got a downlink license to broadcast in India.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Satellite and cable companies would therefore be allowed to broadcast Al Jazeera in the country.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The channel launched on Dish TV in November 2011, and is considering a Hindi-language channel.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Tata Play satellite service broadcasts this on Channel 637 (SD) in India.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] On 26 November 2009, the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission approved "a request to add Al Jazeera English (AJE) to the lists of eligible satellite services for distribution on a digital basis and amends the lists of eligible satellite services accordingly".
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English became available on Rogers Cable, Videotron and Bell Satellite TV on 4 May 2010.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English is available via satellite across all of North America free to air via Globecast on Galaxy 19 on the Ku band in DVB format.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] As of 2011, only a small number of Americans were able to watch the channel on their televisions.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Among the markets where it was available were Bristol County, Rhode Island, Toledo and Sandusky, Ohio, Burlington, Vermont, Houston, Texas, and Washington, DC.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Industry giant Comcast originally planned to carry Al Jazeera English in 2007, but reversed its decision shortly before the channel's launch, citing "the already-saturated television market".
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The two major American satellite providers, DirecTV and Dish Network, had similar plans but also changed their minds, with speculation that the decision may have been influenced by allegations by the Bush administration of "anti-American bias" on the channel.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] With Al Jazeera's coverage of the Egyptian Revolution of 2011, the channel drew acclaim and received renewed attention.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] *The New York Times* reported on 1 February 2011 that 1.6 million U.S. viewers had tuned in via Internet stream, and stated that new discussions were underway with carriers.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The following month, it was announced that Al Jazeera entered carriage negotiations with Comcast and Time Warner Cable.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Salon.com described the channel's English-language coverage as "mandatory viewing for anyone interested in the world-changing events currently happening in Egypt", while *Huffington Post* contributor Jeff Jarvis claimed it was "un-American" for operators to not carry the network.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] When Al Jazeera covered the Libyan Civil War, U.S.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Secretary of State Hillary Clinton noted an increasing American audience for the network, saying that "viewership of Al Jazeera is going up in the United States because it's real news.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] On 1 February 2011, Internet appliance Roku posted on its Facebook page that the English-language Al Jazeera Live would be streaming on Roku devices through a private channel called Newscaster and also through the BBC channel.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] It permitted the announcement following unrest in Egypt so American viewers can watch the latest events going on in the Middle East.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] A Roku user must add the private channel Newscaster from the Roku website.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] On 1 August 2011, Al Jazeera English began airing 23 hours a day in New York City as part of a sublet agreement with cable channel RISE, a former Spanish-language network, which is carried on WRNN-TV's DT2 subchannel (the other hours were used to meet FCC E/I and local programming guidelines).
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The network aired on Time Warner Cable on channel 92 and on Verizon FiOS on channel 481.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] On 2 January 2013, Al Jazeera announced that it had acquired the U.S.-based cable TV channel Current TV for a reported $500 million.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] With this acquisition, Al Jazeera launched a new channel, called Al Jazeera America, with a heavy dose of U.S. domestic news along with Al Jazeera English programming and news, to an estimated 40 million U.S. households—putting it in direct competition with CNN, MSNBC and Fox News Channel.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Due to contracts with U.S. cable and satellite carriers for Al Jazeera America the official Al Jazeera English live stream was geo-blocked in the United States on 18 August 2013.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] With the launch of Al Jazeera America, Al Jazeera English was excluded from all US services carrying or providing the channel, including YouTube, with Al Jazeera America material replacing all Al Jazeera English video content and live streams.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Most Al Jazeera English video content was no longer officially available in the United States.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] In April 2014 the Al Jazeera English show *Empire* was not geo-blocked in the United States.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Shortly after the programs *Indian Hospital*, *Viewfinder*, *Lifelines: The Quest for Global Health* and *Head to Head* were available also.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] These programs were the only AJE shows officially non-geoblocked for American viewing during the time that Al Jazeera America was in existence.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] With the closure of Al Jazeera America in April 2016 it was expected that the official live stream of Al Jazeera English and access to its programmes would eventually be restored to the United States.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The online live stream of Al Jazeera English was made available to viewers in the United States once again in September 2016.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Shortly after launching in 2003, Al Jazeera's English website was hit by hackers who launched denial-of-service attacks.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Aljazeera.com has served as the primary web address for both the Al Jazeera English and former Al Jazeera America websites since early 2011.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The domain name was acquired by Al Jazeera Media Network from Aljazeera Publishing, a Dubai-based media company which previously used the domain as the website for their unrelated publication Aljazeera Magazine.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] This followed after a long-running domain name dispute between the two entities, which included a failed 2005 attempt by Al Jazeera Network to take control of the domain.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Confusion between the two entities resulted in some articles from Al Jazeera magazine being erroneously attributed to the Al Jazeera Network.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] In 2012, 40 percent of the 150 million visits Al Jazeera English's website received originated from the United States.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The Al Jazeera Investigative Unit is a specialized investigative journalism team within Al Jazeera.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The unit is known for producing investigative reports and documentaries on a wide range of global issues, including politics, human rights, corruption, environmental issues, and more.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The documentaries are featured as exclusive specials within their dedicated series Al Jazeera Investigates.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] On 29 December 2013, Egyptian security forces arrested three Al Jazeera English journalists—Australian Peter Greste, Canadian Mohamed Fahmy, and Egyptian Baher Mohamed—at Cairo's Marriott Hotel, accusing them of reporting news damaging to national security.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Despite international outcry and campaigns like #FreeAJStaff, calls for their release from the UN, EU, and the US went unheeded.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The journalists faced a series of trial delays, with questionable evidence, including misleading videos, inaudible audio recordings, and unrelated images.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] On 23 June 2014, Greste and Fahmy received seven-year sentences, while Mohamed was sentenced to 10 years.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The verdict was widely criticized, with global leaders and media outlets denouncing it as a politically motivated attack on press freedom.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Calls for amnesty were rebuffed by Egypt, asserting the independence of its justice system.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Amid mounting pressure, Greste was released and deported to Australia on 1 February 2015.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] On 29 August 2015, the trio faced an additional three-year sentence, sparking international condemnation.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The Canadian government sought Fahmy's pardon and deportation, which was granted on 23 September 2015, alongside a pardon for Mohamed, as part of a larger pardon by Egyptian President el-Sisi for 100 individuals.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The case underscored concerns about press freedom and raised calls for reevaluating foreign aid to Egypt.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] In 2012, Melissa Chan, who served as the longstanding China correspondent for Al Jazeera English, faced expulsion from the country.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Although the Chinese government refrained from publicly disclosing the reasons for her expulsion, it was widely understood that their dissatisfaction stemmed from a documentary aired by the channel that focused on China's prison system.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] The incident prompted inquiries during the Beijing press corps' routine questioning at the Chinese Foreign Ministry's daily press briefing on 8 May 2012.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] However, officials provided no explanation and selectively omitted most related questions when publishing the official transcript.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Following her expulsion, Melissa Chan continued her journalistic career at Al Jazeera America.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Emmy Award-winning journalist Dave Marash resigned from his position in March 2008, saying his exit was due in part to an anti-American bias at the network, which is little seen in the US.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Marash said he felt that attitude more from British administrators than Arabs.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] He said there were other reasons for his exit and was proud of the network's coverage of issues south of the equator, but that he ultimately felt that it was not the right place for him.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] On 12 October 2008, Al Jazeera English broadcast interviews with people attending a Sarah Palin United States presidential election rally in St.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Clairsville, Ohio, with interviewees making comments about Barack Obama such as "he regards white people as trash" and "I'm afraid if he wins, the blacks will take over"...The report received over two million views on YouTube.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al-Jazeera, once viewed skeptically in the U.S, received broad praise for its Egypt coverage, which boosted its American audience and renewed calls for its inclusion on U.S. cable networks.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Additional programming geared towards an American audience includes a day's worth of special coverage marking the 10th anniversary of the terrorist attacks of 11 September 2001.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera has also launched *The Stream*, a show based in Washington D.C. that discusses social media, which targets an American audience.
[src:baduy-people/al-jazeera-english] On 2 January 2013, Al Jazeera purchased the American channel Current TV and rebranded as Al Jazeera America in August 2013.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] The **Alas people** (Batak Alas-Kluet: *Ukhang Alas*) are an indigenous Batak sub-ethnic group from Southeast Aceh Regency, Aceh, Sumatra, Indonesia.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] The Alas are found in the Gunung Leuser, Ketambe, and Alas River areas.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] The Alas (*ukhang Alas* or *kalak Alas*) are an agrarian people, who cultivate rice on irrigated fields, but some grow cash crops in gardens.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] Freshwater fishing in Alas River or brooks used to be indispensable as a source of animal protein, while raising fish in ponds is becoming important.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] Between the 15th and 17th centuries, they converted to Islam, The Alas society is a patrilineal descent society; each belongs to one exogamous clan.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] Sometimes an Alas village (*kute*) consists of a single clan, while several clans could frequently be observed in one village.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] As Alas clan names suggest, the Alas people have composite origins.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] At the final stage of the Aceh War in 1904, Gotfried Coenraad Ernst van Daalen started on his campaign to Gayoland, Alasland, and Batakland in order to establish the Dutch colonial control over them.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] After demolishing 7 forts and killing nearly 1300 inhabitants in Gayoland, his Korps Marechaussee te voet appeared in the Alas valley on 10 June 1904.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] On 14 June 1904, the Dutch troops demolished the fort of Kuta Reh, killing 313 indigenous men, 189 women, and 59 children, while 2 Dutch soldiers were killed.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] On 20 June 1904, then, they demolished the fort of Likat, killing 220 men, 124 women, and 88 children, while a single soldier was killed.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] Indeed, the village of Likat was one of Gayonese migrants into the Alas valley.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] On 24 June 1904, finally, they demolished the fort of Kute Lengat Baru, killing 338 men, 186 women, and 130 children, including the acting southern local lord, while 3 soldiers were killed.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] On 29 June 1904, Gotfried Coenraad Ernst van Daalen summoned the northern local lord and the son of the deceased southern local lord with all other Alas chiefs and headmen to the village of Pedesi in front of him, to declare that the whole of Alasland belonged to the Dutch East Indies.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] During this campaign, Henricus Marinus Neeb, a military doctor, took many photos, including ones of fighting scenes, marching through the tropical rain forest, local fishing activities, traditional houses, mosques, and so on.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] The Alas people uses the Alas language (*Cekhok Alas*) on a daily basis.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] The Alas language is most closely related to the language of the Kluet people in Aceh Selatan Regency, and often, these two languages are unified under a single label Alas–Kluet.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] Together with Karo and Dairi, Alas–Kluet belongs to the northern branch of the Batak subgroup of the Austronesian language family.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] It is estimated that 80,000 people spoke the language in 2000.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] Although Alas people live in Aceh Province, the language they use is entirely distinct from Acehnese.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] Each Alas person belongs to a patrilineal clan or descent group (*mekhge*).
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] It has its own name, which is used as surname of the Alas people.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] In 1988 there were 27 clans as follows, but some had already had no member.
[src:baduy-people/alas-people] Bangko, Cibekho, Deski, Keling, Kepale Dese, Kekhuas, Pagan, and Selian, are believed to be original among the Alas.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The **Baduy** (Badui: *Urang Baduy/Urang Kanékés*; Indonesian: *Orang Baduy/Orang Sunda Baduy*), also known as **Badui** or **Kanékés**, are an indigenous Sundanese ethnic group native to the southeastern part of Banten, specifically Lebak Regency, Banten, Indonesia.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The term *baduy* is a short form derived from *baduyut* in the Baduy language.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] It is a native Sundanese term that refers to an endemic vine plant of western Java (*Trichosanthes villosa*), used as a herbal medicine since ancient times.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] As part of the Sundanese family, *baduyut* also bears the same meaning in Old and Modern Sundanese.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] It is likely that in ancient times, there was a river called Baduyut, as the term *Cibaduyut* (ᮎᮤᮘᮓᮥᮚᮥᮒ᮪) itself literally means "Baduyut River" in the Sundanese language, thus it is possible that this tribe was named after the river.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Baduy people sometimes prefer to be called *Urang Kanekes* (lit.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] "Kanekes people") or *Urang Cibeo* (lit.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] "Cibeo people") instead, as these are the names of their cultural regions or villages.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] There is also a theory suggesting that the word *baduy* was initially an exonym used by outsiders to refer to these tribal groups, stemming from the idea that the Dutch equated them with Bedouin Arabs.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] No foreigners are allowed to meet the Inner Baduy, though the Outer Baduy do foster some limited contacts with the outside world.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] *Dangka Baduy* have sustained contact with the outside world and no longer live in the Kanekes area.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] It is subdivided into two sectors: the Baduy Dalam area is 2,749 hectares, while Baduy Luar is slightly smaller, at 2,387 hectares.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Based on 2017 data from Statistics Indonesia, the Baduy population consisted of 11,699 individuals, or 3,413 families.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] However, by 2023, that number had declined to only 9,558 individuals.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] They are centred at the drainage basin of the Ci Ujung and Cikanekes rivers, around the foothills of Kendeng volcano, within the settlement of Kanekes, in Leuwidamar district, Lebak Regency, Banten, a distance of 65 km (40 mi) from Serang and 172 km (107 mi) from Jakarta, the nation's capital.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The region, situated at an elevation of 300–500 meters (980–1,640 ft) above sea level, consists of hilly topography, with surfaces that reach up to an average of 45% slope, with volcanic (north), precipitate (centre), and mixed soil (south).
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The average temperature is 20 °C (68 °F).
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Baduy homeland is contained within 50 km2 (19 sq mi) of hilly forest area.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The three main settlements of Inner Baduy are Cikeusik, Cikertawana, and Cibeo.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] They fall within a protected area, as designated by Lebak Regional Regulation No.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The region features a hilly topography, with elevations ranging from 325 meters above sea level (a.s.l.) in the north to 900 meters a.s.l. in the south, where its highest point is found.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Geologically, the area is primarily formed by quaternary volcanic deposits, specifically the Baduy and Cimapag formation, along with volcanic rock from Endut mountain, claystone, and Citorek tuff.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] These formations constitute the Bayah Mountains zone, which is commonly composed of sand, silt, mud, and crop residue.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The region's average annual temperature is 26.5 °C, with minimal seasonal fluctuation; temperatures typically range from a minimum of 26.1 °C in February to a maximum of 26.8 °C in May, September, and October.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The average monthly rainfall is 171.1 mm, categorizing it as medium.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] This rainfall contributes to an average relative humidity of 81%, with the lowest levels (76%) occurring in August and September and the highest (85%) in February.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The area is located within the Ciujung watershed, with the Ciujung River traversing the region from its forested southern upstream to the northern downstream.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The area encompasses eleven sub-watersheds.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The native language of the Baduy people, Baduy, is most closely related and sometimes considered to be a dialect of Sundanese.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Native speakers are dispersed in regions around the Mount Kendeng, Rangkasbitung district of Lebak Regency, Pandeglang Regency, and Sukabumi, West Java.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] It is estimated that there are 11,620 speakers as of 2010.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] In order to communicate with outsiders, the Baduy people tend to speak Sundanese and sometimes Indonesian to some degree of fluency.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Inner Baduy in Kanekes village are mostly illiterate, hence, their customary religious belief system and ancestral folk tales are preserved in the form of oral tradition.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Formal education for Baduy children is seen by Baduy people as a violation of their traditional customs, and they have so far refused the Indonesian government's proposals to build educational facilities in their villages.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] As a result, few Baduy people are educated or able to read or write.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Baduy people's creation story describes the Earth's genesis as a viscous, transparent substance they call *ngenclong*, which was initially the size of a single rice grain.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] This gradually hardened and expanded, eventually forming the Sasaka Domas, a megalithic structure they consider to be the core and center of the Earth and the starting point for all life.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] They also believe this to be the place where the first human was sent to Earth, becoming the ancestor of all peoples.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Baduy also believe that the *ngenclong* separated into different parts.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The part that went up to form the sky is called *Buana Nyungcung*, and the part that went down is known as *Buana Larang*, which serves as a hell.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Between these two realms lies *Buana Tengah*, the home of humans, trees, and animals, as well as *Buana Suci Alam Padang*, where the rice goddesses reside.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] *Buana Suci Alam Padang* consists of 18 layers.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The highest layer is called *Bumi Suci Alam Kahiyangan* or *Mandala Hiyang*, and it is where Nyi Pohaci Sanghiyang Asri and Sunan Ambu live.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] According to their belief system, the Baduy people regard themselves as descendants of Batara Cikal, one of seven deities, or gods, who was sent to Earth.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] One hypothesis suggests the Baduy community originated from people in Banten who fled the spread of Islam after the fall of the Sunda Kingdom.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] These refugees are thought to have initially settled along the Cibaduy River, which is believed to be the source of their name.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Kruseman has proposed that the Baduy are an indigenous group of the Banten region, he has also speculated that they moved deeper into the forest after 1579 CE.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Baduy themselves have rejected the claim that they are descended from Pajajaran, as in their culture, the name is used to refer to malevolent spirits, which they ward off using specific chants.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Another theory suggests that, before the establishment of the sultanate, the western tip of Java island played an important role for the Sunda Kingdom, with Banten serving as a large trading port.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Various types of vessels entered the Ciujung River, most of which were used to transport crops harvested from the interior regions.Therefore, the ruler of the region, Prince Pucuk Umun, believed that the river's sustainability needed to be maintained.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] An army of highly trained royal troops was commanded to guard and manage the dense and hilly jungle areas in the Mount Kendeng region, which may have been the origin of the Baduy.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The theory was strengthened by a long-held tradition called *seba puun*, where the village leader (*puun*), would go to the capital to report his village's condition to the king.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] This practice has continued to the present day, with reports being made to the regent of Lebak.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The discrepancy between the two theories has led to the notion that in the past, the identity and historicity of the Baduy had been intentionally concealed in order to protect the community from attacks by the Sunda Kingdom's enemies.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Van Tricht, a doctor who had done medical research in the area in 1928, denied this theory, however.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] According to him, the Baduy are natives of the region and have strongly resisted external influences.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Baduy themselves also refuse to acknowledge that they originate from the fugitives of Pajajaran.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] According to Danasasmita and Djatisunda, the Baduy people are local to the settlements that are officially mandated by the king, because the people are obliged to preserve the *kabuyutan* (ancestral or ancestral worship).
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The religion of the Baduy is known as *Agama Sunda Wiwitan* and is rooted in ancestral worship and honoring or worshiping spirits of natural forces.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] According to the *kokolot* (elders) of Cikeusik village, Kanekes people are not adherents of Hinduism or Buddhism.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] However, in its development, this faith is influenced by and has incorporated elements of Hinduism, and to some extent, Islam.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The core of this belief is shown by the existence of *pikukuh*, or the absolute customary provisions practiced in the daily lives of the Kanekes people.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Baduy also observe many mystical taboos.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] They are forbidden to kill, steal, lie, commit adultery, get drunk, eat food at night, take any form of conveyance, wear flowers or perfumes, accept gold or silver, touch money, or cut their hair.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] In agriculture, they practice *pukukuh* by not changing the contour of the land for their fields, so much so that the way of farming is very simple; not cultivating the land using plows or forming terraces, but only using hoe-farming methods, that is, with sharpened bamboo.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] In the construction of houses, the contouring of the soil surface is also left as is, therefore, the poles of the Kanekes houses are often not of the same length.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The words and actions of the Baduy people are expected to be honest, innocent, without beating around the bush, and devoid of bargaining in trade.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Other taboos relate to defending Baduy lands against invasion: they may not grow sawah (wet rice), use fertilizers, raise cash crops, use modern tools for working *ladang* soil, or keep large domestic animals.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The most important religious object for the Kanekes people is the Arca Domas, whose location is kept secret and is considered sacred.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Kanekes people visit the site to worship once a year in the month of Kalima, which, in 2003, coincided with the month of July.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Only *Pu'un*, or the highest customary chairman and several elected members of the community, will follow the entourage to worship.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Rainwater is stored in a mortar container in the Arca Domas complex.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] If it is found to be clear at the time of worship, then it is a sign for the Kanekes people that there will be plenty of rain that year, and the harvest will be bountiful.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Conversely, if the mortar container is dry or the water is turbid, then it is a sign of crop failure.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Islamic influence has also penetrated the religion of the Baduy Luar, especially in the Cicakal Girang villages, which are inhabited primarily by Muslims.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Baduy people are closely related to the Sundanese people, although they embrace Sunda Wiwitan as their belief system and isolate themselves to preserve their traditional lifestyle.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Sundanese themselves mostly embrace Islam as their religion.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The regions where the Baduy live are called *mandala*s, from a Sanskrit word meaning "center".
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] A characteristic of the Kanekes Dalam people is the color of their clothing—white and dark blue, as well as the wearing of a white headband.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] They follow the rigid *buyut* taboo system very strictly, (see § Religion and beliefs) and thus have made very little contact with the outside world.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The priests of this community, known as *pu'un*, are the only ones allowed to visit the most sacred ground of the Baduy, which lies on Gunung Kendeng, in a place called Arca Domas.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The *Panamping*, also known as *Baduy Luar* or *Kanekes Luar* (meaning "Outer Kanekes"), make up the remainder of the Baduy population, living in 22 villages and acting as a barrier to stop visitors from contacting the more reclusive community.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] They also follow the rigid taboo system but not as strictly as the Kanekes Dalam, and they are more willing to accept modern influences into their daily lives.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Baduy Luar have traded their traditional blue-black homespun clothes for conventional clothing.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The use of money, batteries, and toys are increasingly common, particularly in northern villages, and a few people from these communities work as seasonal farmhands or find jobs in major cities like Jakarta, Bogor, and Bandung.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Additionally, while raising livestock remains banned, some outer villages eat meat caught with the help of trained hunting dogs.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Some Kanekes Dalam have become Kanekes Luar, either through intermarriage or as a result of breaking Kanekes Dalam customary laws.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] There are two Kanekes Luar settlements, namely Padawaras (Cibengkung) and Sirahdayeuh (Cihadam), which function as a buffer between the Kanekes Dalam and the outside world.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Kanekes community recognizes two governing systems: the national system, which is in accordance with the laws of Indonesia, and the customary system, which abides by the customs of the community.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Both are combined or acculturated in such a way that there is no conflict.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Conventionally, the Kanekes people are led by a head of settlement, who is referred to as *jaro pamarentah*.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Customarily, the Kanekes people fall under the leadership of the *pu'un*, who can be found in three settlements, or *tangtu*.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The position is passed down through generations, but not necessarily from a father to his children; it can also be handed down to other relatives.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The governing term of a *pu'un* is not specified; instead, it depends on a person's ability to hold on to the position.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The main livelihood of the Baduy people is rice farming.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] This is divided into four phases over the course of a year: harvesting, post-harvest rituals, land clearing, and planting and field maintenance.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] During harvesting, no outsiders are allowed in the villages for around three months.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Baduy do not fertilize or irrigate their crops, relying solely on rain.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Baduy also earn extra income from selling the fruits they gather in the jungle, such as durian and tamarind-plum, as well as wild honey.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Kanekes community, who until the present have adhered strictly to their customs, has not been entirely isolated from the developments of the outside world.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] They became aware of the establishment of the Sultanate of Banten, which automatically annexed the Kanekes people into the kingdom's territory of power.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] As a sign of obedience to and recognition of these authorities, the Kanekes community routinely perform the *seba* ceremony each year, which involves delivering crops such as rice and fruit to the Governor of Banten (and formerly to the Governor of West Java) through the regent of Lebak.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] In agriculture, the Kanekes Luar people interact closely with outsiders in affairs such as leasing of land and laborers.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] In the past, trading was done by barter, but nowadays, the community uses the national currency, the rupiah.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The Kanekes people sell fruits, honey, and sugar palm through middlemen.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] They also purchase necessities that they do not produce themselves from markets.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] Today, visitors to the Kanekes customary region are increasing, with a large number consisting of high school or college students.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] These are welcomed into the community and can even spend the night there, provided that they abide by local rules.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] These include a ban on taking pictures within the Kanekes Dalam areas as well as a prohibition on the use of soap or toothpaste in the rivers.
[src:baduy-people/baduy-people] The customary region of the Kanekes people remains forbidden to non-Indonesians, however, including journalists.
